properties.abstract: Viewed from Brienz, Axalphoren is first of all a mighty, unwelcoming rock face, but a secluded valley and steep grassy slopes are hidden behind it. As the enchanting Hinterburgseeli and the carved wooden figures along the way are worth a visit, we include the trail along the little lake in the main intinerary although it is a detour. Between October and December and between January and May the whole area may be inaccessible due to military target practice.
properties.subtitle: Between rock faces and steep grassy slopes

segments.description: From Axalp follow the marked hiking trail to Hinterburgseeli. Along the way you see wooden figures carved by students of the wood carving school Brienz (www.holzbildhauerei.ch). From Hinterburgseeli the trail climbs westward in many turns and then above rock faces up to the alp Urserli (1805 m). Now continue southward to Sattel (1959 m). This part of the trail is on karst limestone, which can be sharp-edged as well as slippery. In wet conditions caution is advised, the steel cable notwithstanding. Continue on the mountain hiking trail via Scheitegg onto the western ridge of Axalphoren. Now climb, first on the ridge, then, in the steep grassy slope, on a narrowing path to a point some metres below the western summit (2307 m).

segments.description: From below the western summit (2307 m) continue in the path, which from now on is much fainter and, above all, more exposed where it is on the very steep grassy slopes. Below another, small secondary summit continue into a breach below the main summit. From this breach climb easily (IâII), but exposed to the highest point. Descend the same way back to the point below the western summit.

segments.description: Western summit (2307 m): it is easier than the main summit and does not require any climbing. However, the summit is exposed. On the way to Axalphoren do not traverse the south slopes, but take the western ridge up to the western summit. T4, saves 15 mins.
segments.title: To the western summit

segments.description: On the now better visible path descend back to the bifurcation on the western ridge.
